segments.text: Testing, testing, Friday, Friday.
Testing, testing.
When we quit last Friday, we had you finish your freshman year.
What did you do that summer after your freshman year?
Well, as I indicated earlier, I had this agreement with my parents who couldn't support me, but they offered to pay me, I think, $600 room and board to work on the farm that summer.
So that's what I did, and I worked pretty hard.
One of the interesting experiences that was, the work was pretty hard and pretty hot in the summer, but we did have a good tradition of about a two hour break at midday to get away from the heat.
Started early, had dinner, and then took a nice lap and worked till late, you know, dark at night.
made it very difficult when you came back to September and had a one o'clock class to stay awake.
Your work day on the farm began at what time?
Daylight?
Yeah, daylight.
I guess that was before daylight saving.
They used daylight saving time during the war, but they dropped it after the war.
So it was basically, we had a very heavy routine.
We had usually up around six, and at that time my sister had

already left so there were only three of us and it'd be an hour hour and a half of doing the chores because we had cows about 20 cows to milk chickens to feed hogs to feed sheep everything else my mother usually left about 20 minutes before and after about an hour and a half we ate breakfast and that's why i'm still a big breakfast eater because you were really ready to eat and then you went out and do the fields and then what had to be done in the fields worked till noon had a pretty good meal at noon and in the summertime you rest at
during the period, during the heat of the day, and then went back out around 2 or 2.30 and worked till dark, which was 7, 8 o'clock.
So you were grateful for the opportunity to come back to school.
I've often heard many Aggies say that many Baptist ministers got their call in the middle of a patch in August.
All right, you came back as a sophomore and lived where?
Well, the old company that I had been in had been broken up and had been assigned to D Artillery.
I think just arbitrarily.
I don't know that I had a choice.
I don't remember having a choice.
But that was the year, this was 46, when the things really bulged, because that's when the veterans really came back in.
And there was a huge housing shortage.
And that's when they went to three to a room.
And if you're familiar with the dormitories over in the new dorm area, the core area, those rooms are barely big enough for two.
And they actually put a triple, another bunk on top of the two bunks to save a little space.
There really wasn't much space for a table or anybody else.
So it was a very difficult circumstance.
And of course, my own situation was working in the library.
I still did most of my studying at the library and stayed in the room just the minimum period that I had.
And also, as I said, probably escaped some of the activities that I didn't want to participate in.
How did three roommates decide who slept on the top and who on the bottom?
Some of it was tar plays, I guess, and some of it was, I think most of the time it was by flipping coins or something like that.
And we took turns.
I think that's what we usually, I mean, we often took turns, I think.
And some just had preferences for one thing or the other.
Was there an effort made to have three study tables in that crowd?
I think they managed to put a third one in there in front of the window or something like that.
And they had only two closets, which we were even starting off with, but not

even too large for one person but it was it was not very easy to operate in and the other of course the other problem as i indicated with all these veterans coming back even those who had not performed too well academically before they went to the war most of them had gotten married and gotten the gi bill and they were determined to make their mark and many many who had barely passing averages suddenly were straight-a students and it was pretty
Was the temporary housing for the veterans over around the football stadium, was that yet there?
Well, they used the project houses.
Okay.
They used those, but then they built on the north side, they brought in all those barracks, and that's where most of the veterans lived.
And there were a lot of barracks on campus about where the Brocker building in that area were used for classrooms.
I remember many classrooms were held in.
pretty unsatisfactory.

I mean, they couldn't be cooled, well, we didn't have air conditioning, and even pretty hard to heat, but there were a lot of, just one barrack, all temporary buildings, and the housing, well, that wasn't even too long ago when they turned, that served A&M for many, many years for barrack student housing.
Do you remember seeing some veterans who were badly injured hobbling to class?
Uh, not too many.
There were some, and of course they loved to kid the younger ones of us that hadn't had all the experiences that they had and made fun about it and so forth.
But they also, I think, were good role models because they studied and they were in the business.
And you were settled into your major by now?
I think so, yeah, pretty well.
I was headed in that direction.

I guess the two general things that we hadn't commented on, and I'm not sure when these happened, there was a famous revolt, senior revolt, where the seniors, because of the crackdown on hazing, as I recall, and the, the Oprah's was president at the time, and he cracked down on, and the senior commission, who were commission officers, decided they would push him in a corner by offering their resignations, and
It probably happened my freshman year.
It could have been my sophomore year.

But anyway, the seniors had everybody fall out late one evening, 9, 10 o'clock, with bearing torches, marched on the president's home, and they, with a great deal of ceremony, they handed him their resignations as protest to this crackdown on core activities.
And to their utter surprise, he accepted it.
And I didn't know really what the, I was just marching in and marching back.
But anyway, that was one of the interesting things that happened.
Also during this period, it might have been about my sophomore year, we had a lot of publicity focused on campus that there was a Life magazine came down and did a story.
and did a picture of the entire corps assembled in front of the mess hall.
I'm in that picture.
I still find myself.
Have you ever seen that?
Yeah.
And that was a big activity.
Anyway, in the sophomore year, as I said, that was the year I started working in the library full-time and enjoyed that aspect of it.
I may have had been for that.
I don't know if I could have either paid for my education because I

probably averaged working about 30 hours a week mostly in the evening like when I got to the after I did my apprenticeship running the stacks you moved up a little and finally got to the reserve desk which was the ideal place to be because in a three hour period you might have an actual work of maybe a half an hour or 45 minutes and then occasionally somebody would come in but the idea was the books were on reserve for two hour use
The student could come in, get the book, and then turn it in.
You'd have to shelve it and take care of that aspect of it.
But it was a wonderful place to study.
It was quiet, and the resources were handy and all that.
Now, the library was a quiet place to escape from hazing, wasn't it?
Well, yeah, for a lot of people.
That's what I mean.
But it was a wonderful place, and especially with three to a room.
It was a wonderful refuge.
I probably would have gone there anyway if I could have.
But see, the core of regulations was that unless you had a job, you were expected to be in your room.
Oh.
Even as a sophomore.
Now, you didn't have the, you weren't tied down where you had to stick at your desk.
But you had to stay in your room, too.
I mean, you could move around and you could visit with colleagues and so forth.
But they were also enforcers.
They'd walk up and down the hall periodically to make sure of the freshmen.
The freshmen always had to keep their door open.
But could you claim that you were in the library doing homework?
Yes, well, yes, occasionally.
But then you could only do it.
But if you worked, I mean, you put that on your schedule.
You placed your schedule on your door so the upperclassmen would know how to account for you.
And if there was a vacant period, you'd have to account for it.
And it was nice to feel at work and so forth, where you could escape some of that activity.
And the librarian at this point was whom?
I can't remember for sure.
If you name the names, I might recognize them.
I don't remember.
He was a former English professor.
Tommy Mayo?
Mayo.
Oh, he still was?
Okay.
Maybe.
Because he was the director for a long, long time.
But I had very little contact at my level with him.
Describe the environment of the library at that time.
Well, it was basically the Cushing part, as you know.
I'm not even sure.
I can't even remember as much where the downstairs were used, where those exhibition rooms are now.
The main center was the second floor, where they had on the west side, as it still is there, this huge long reading room.
That's where the reserve desk was located at the entrance.
And then, on the east side, they had the circulation desk, where the students ran and accepted the request for books and ran the hand stacks and brought them back to whoever requested them.
Was there ever any hijink, any pranks in the library?
Not that I'm aware of.
I'm not aware of any.
Speaking of pranks, of course, you've heard this before.
Sometimes with the tacit blessing I guess of the juniors and seniors, some sophomores really got out of line.
I mean they were the enforcers in terms of the paddling and the hazing and so forth.
Of course it was presumed that the juniors and seniors put them up to it to some extent, but sometimes a little sometimes some sophomores got a little too enthusiastic and the
the way for the freshmen to strike back was roundouts.
You knew that.
They'd get a wastebasket full of water, and usually it was water, but if he was really obnoxious, sometimes it was treated water.
There were some human
some human fluid.
And it often really helped.
It cooled off the ardor in terms of some of theanother practicethis was mostly done on piers.
You'd short-sheet people, if you've heard of that.
That was some of the activities.
I told you about hazing the students always trying to play pranks on the campus cops, the KKs as we called them, wherever we could, because they were regarded as not too
intellectually swift, and that was some of the side activities.
Now, was the, did y'all call it the quack shack then?
Yeah.
Describe it.
Well, I had a very, I guess it was, no, it was later on, it was generally lowly regarded by the students.
I mean, you went there as a last resort.
In fact, I could tell you a story.
I almost died there myself later on.
I might as well have entered.
I think I was further along.

but I got a very bad strep infection, it might have been my junior year, and antibiotics had just become available, but they were treating me here, they had only one aged doctor as I remember, and maybe a nurse or two, and that was it, but they had a hospital, a little, several beds, and I was in there, and which we've discovered since then that I
I'm allergic to sulfa, but that's what they were treating me with, sulfa.
Same here.

Instead of penicillin, I mean, they didn't... About that time there was a colleague of mine from my same community who was one class ahead of me, who we started riding, he had a car and I didn't, sometimes that was my ticket to get home.
Anyway, he was concerned about me and even though we didn't live in the same dorm or anything, he looked after me and he was

raving with these people you've got to do something because at that time i was not even conscious and he took it on himself to take me out of there and took me home to the family doctor who gave me penicillin and two days later i was back in school i mean you know the penicillin was really marvellous but i think the uh i guess the budget was such they had it was an elderly gentleman who was here and as i said it was generally a place to be avoided
I guess if you were an accident, you were carried there.
And I guess anything more serious was taken to the local hospital or something like this.
Now, since you, as a sophomore, were not a hazer, did your buddies, did your classmates look down on you?
Did they tease you about it?
No, no particular problem.
There were always enough that were eager enough to, I guess it was their revenge for what they had done.
experience as freshman, but I didn't see it as that way.

I thought, you know, sometimes the cycle has to be broken, but no, I don't think so, and as I said, I kept, you know, I was more interested in academics, I have to indicate, and I tried to keep as low a profile as possible in terms of the core activities.
I didn't have anything against them, but I felt the primary purpose of coming here was an education, and I
felt some of that wasn't contributing to the education.

Another thing I guess I could comment on was, and you've probably heard this too, and I had visited, because I park in that particular area, with some of the bonfire leaders in the last several years.
If they had continued the tradition as we had it when we were here, there wouldn't have been a problem as far as I see it.
The tradition then was you had a good big bonfire, but you did no work on it.

absolutely none until the second last game which was usually at that time there was a flat pattern with TCU which was about a weekend a week it was about 10 11 days before the TU game and everybody went out and did the work then but we built one layer which you know couldn't fall I mean just one cone layer made a pretty good fire and that was it we were not allowed to work on the other

And the other, there were some other traditions, as you're probably aware, when we played SMU, all the freshmen had to wear spurs, made out of coat hangers with bottle caps so they'd, you know, spur the ponies and that type of thing, and there were some other traditions like that, that every time, you only look forward to the next game, you never look beyond the second, I mean, beyond the next game, and went on from there.
But I often say if they'd have kept with it,

didn't get competitive in seeing how high they could get and I've been observing this the last several years that you know this is an accident waiting to happen and I've told told several people I have a good engineering friend I play tennis with who is a structural engineer and he's he has had filed numerous reports pointing out that you know this was an accident waiting to happen but anyway I think they ought to go back to if they want to have a bonfire have a modest one and it still makes a pretty good fire.
And your work on the bonfire was where?
Were you a cutter, a hauler, or?
Well, it really, it was more of a scrounging operation.
I mean, we picked up, there was trash in there, too.
I mean, there were some logs, but I mean, I think it started out with just trash.
Oh, before the war, I know.
Yeah, and then later on, they started making a mixture of it, but we were told, I mean, that was one of the hazing, if you see a toothpick, pick it up.
It's something to put on the bonfire, and so people just kept gathering, and I guess the cutting started about that time,
But we had no machinery, cranes and all of that stuff.
We did everything ourselves.
And it was pretty much a big effort right at that time.
Of course, usually it was rainy and sloppy and everything.
Now, how did you carry it to the bonfire site?
On shoulders.
I mean, a gang of 10 or 12 people, there was a big lock, and you'd push it up manually.
I mean, there was no machinery whatsoever.
All right, before the war, I've had some people tell me that they borrowed from the railroad station those little carts.
Yeah, I think that might have been true.
Yeah, they might have used some of those.
And it was in front of the MSC.
In the drill, on the drill field?
It started out, yeah, it was in the, yeah, that's where it was.
I can't remember when it was, it might have been while I was here.
They changed it to the other drill field over here behind Duncan.
But starting out it was on the parade ground in front of the MSC, yeah.
Let's see, were you, didn't, did Eisenhower come to visit during your student days as a general?
I can't remember.
I would have remembered, I think, if you had.
I was trying to remember when.
I don't know what the year was.
Let's see.
Academically, who became your counselor, advisor?
Who did you turn to for advice?
What to take?
Well, I had this earlier advisor in agricultural engineering as I got to, I guess, going more to animal science.
I never really had one.
I of course made an acquaintance with the department head and became a lifelong friend, Dr. Miller, who was head department head, and there were other people, O.D.
Butler, Bill Warren, who's back here, who was head of the department at Auburn, I guess they moved back here.
All right, who, as you look back on it, what were the factors that led you toward your major?

I guess basically my 4-H experience because I had, I had sheet projects and a lot of hard projects and I was just particularly interested in that field and I guess at that time, well I guess I was pretty well aiming toward becoming a county agent or preparing myself to come on and
The animal aspects of a county agent's work are pretty important.
I mean, you can go either ironic orif you go animal, you're a little weak in the other, but you have to pick ityou still get a balanced course.
Who were the key faculty members and or courses that shaped your Well, I don't know if it shaped it, but I certainly can recall some for one extreme or the other.
And I guess I would have to say the best single professor that I ever encountered was Tom Harrington in chemistry, freshman chemistry.
I took that as the second year here, because I told you we had to switch.
We took the practical courses.

And I was told that the conventional wisdom of Aggies was that chemistry, there were records of people taking it five, six times or finally going to a junior college or somewhere and getting it transferred.
and it was a very tough course, and I was told that I was hopelessly going to be lost because I never had high school chemistry.
I took high school physics.
For some reason, because of the switch from a rural school to another, I couldn't get it in, and they said, you know, you're going to die in this thing.
Well, I really didn't want to take it again.

And so I really studied hard, and then later on I visited with Dr. Harrington about it, and he said, you were better off the way you were than the ones who had it in high school, because they thought they had it made, and after about four weeks, they were in new territory, and they hadn't really learned to study it.
But I made good grades in chemistry, but a part of it was because I really worked at it,
And Tom Harrington was just a wonderful lecturer.
What made him a wonderful lecturer?
He had a dynamic voice.
He was enthusiastic.
He, you know, kept your interest.
I remember, you know, I guess it's still that way, chemistry lecture room, you're familiar with it.
I guess it holds, what, 250, 300 people?
Yeah.
Very easy to go to sleep in there, huh?
And I guess sometimes, but it was hard to sleep with him because he was such a dynamic professor.

But I remember one time he filled a balloon with some, had all these gas outlets on the laboratory, filled the balloon one time and raised it up and then put a Bunsen burner up to it and it popped so loud the dust came out of the cracks of the building and that kept a lot of people from going to sleep from that because they almost had heart attacks when that went on.
But he was a wonderful professor.
Did he have any key attributes in terms of you must do this or that or you may not do?
No, I mean... What if you went to sleep?
Did he wake you up?

Well, I don't, it was, as I said, pretty hard to go to sleep under him because he was such a good lecturer, and of course you better take good notes because the tests were, you know, pretty much all the material presented in the lecture, but
I actually enjoyed it.
Did he have a student nickname?
Did the students give him a nickname?
Not that I remember.
I've often thought how almost everybody else had a nickname, but I've never heard one for him.
No, I can't remember.
And as unlike anybody else.
There was not a lot of entertainment here on the campus.
We had movies on Saturday night for 25 cents in Guyon Hall.
I guess there was a campus theater, but I think they charged more.

and couldn't afford it, but the students were always looking for some entertainment, and professors were fair game in terms of the observation, and this is, I know his name, but I don't want to mention it, but there was a stereotypical math, absent-minded math professor who lived in one of the houses here on the campus, but he was single, he didn't have a family, and he always rode his bicycle.
Have you heard this story?
rode his bicycle to classes back and forth.
And he had, the students always, I mean not always, but there was usually a group gathered to see this daily procedure.
He'd come back home, the garage didn't have a door where the car comes in.
He didn't have a car, he just had a bike.
The door was off, it was open to the street, but there was a little side door, like a regular house door,
that he came up to, carefully unlocked, opened the door, pushed the bike in, closed the door, and locked it.
You could see all of this open.
And I don't know if he just did it to entertain the students or if he was really that out of it.
They had another story about him that one time he accidentally bumped into a student, ran into a student biking.
And after the student assured himself nobody was hurt, the professor asked him, he said, do you remember which way I was going?
Because if I was going that way, I was coming from home.
But those kind of things, as I said, we were desperate for entertainment.
What did you and your buddies do for fun?
Say, on a weekend or...
I always worked.
I mean, every weekend, unless there was a football game, I still, you had to go to a football game.
As a corps member, you had to go to conference games.
And, of course, when the game was here, you had to participate.
And that was, I guess, about the main thing.
Very rarely did I go to the movies with friends.
Occasionally, I mean, there was some intramural, they were very strong on intramural activities, which was probably good.
One of the big, big activities after a big rain, there was always mud football, you know, where you tackle and you could follow the slash and you somewhat needed a shower after that.
The other thing that was, I guess, shocking for me, particularly in my freshman year, was the
In freshman athletics, they have very high requirements, and even though I worked hard on the farm, I didn't run a lot.
They had the expectation when you came here to pass first semester of PE, you had, they had a track over on the other side, they called it the Miles and Seven.
You had to run that in a certain prescribed time, and if you're not
in shape, you know, that takes a while, and they had Putnam, do you remember the name?
Is that the name?
Yeah.

Anyway, he would start us off and then, you know, pass us all up and be there to clock us in, but I think the rule was you had to make it under, I'm not sure of this, under thirteen minutes to get an A or B, and between thirteen and fifteen you'd get a C or D depending on how you did on everything else, but that was

a huge requirement for people and luckily I had heard about it and I started on the farm working up to getting in shape and they had you know so many push-ups chin-ups and all I guess it was from the military they were you know the basic physical standards that they kept but they were fairly rugged but there was a lot of uh if uh activity
I said there were intramurals.
The Corps always, after say the period of between five and six in the evening, there were usually some intramural activity that you were expected to participate in.
But on a Saturday night when there wasn't anything scheduled, you and your buddies didn't go to the clay pits or?
No, I never did.
I mean, I'm sure the others did and there was, I heard about Ed's, I never knew where that was, but as I said, most of my time was spent working and
I guess later on we did begin to notice the interest in the opposite sex and you've heard of these stories about how it was handled when you had dates.
I mean I did I think have two or three dates come down on home games and you knew about evacuating a dormitory and you'd have to furnish the sheets and then the
The joke was that you wouldn't wash those sheets for about a month because they had this wonderful smell of perfume and so forth.
Yeah, one whole dorm was evacuated, and you had to find a place to sleep.
And how did the Aggies treat those young ladies?
Oh, with great respect, tremendous respect.
And it was a real honor for the ladies to come here.
I mean, that was a coup as far as their peers were back home were concerned.
And, of course, they were to the traditions with TWU,
particularly when we went to Dallas or Fort Worth.
They came down in mass, and there was some interaction.
Of course, there was that earlier tradition of where you wrote your counterpart with the same box number.
Sometimes that led to disaster.
Sometimes it led to, I guess, enduring relationships, as I heard.
I have heard you have, too.
On Sunday morning, did you go to worship?
Yes, I started to.
I really didn't have much of a religious upbringing in my home.
I mean, my

my mother had been I guess of the Protestant or Lutheran persuasion my father had been Catholic but his father had fallen out with the church and they really didn't do much but I felt it's part of my education and I started I guess with the Lutheran but then the Presbyterians had the better facilities over in the YMCA they used the and so I fell in and to this day I'm a Presbyterian because of that
But I went, you know, I went most Sunday mornings.
Did you know Mr. Cashin?
Oh, yes.
Describe him.
We don't know howI don't have much about him.
Well, he was the YMCA.
I mean, that was it, and he ran that
I guess he was Presbyterian, too.
I guess, I remember the Lutherans had the second choice of facilities.
They had to meet in a different room, but they had a regular chapel that the Presbyterians used because they were one of the few churches that didn't have their own facility here.
What about his, what did he, what physically, what did he look like and his personality?
Well, he was, as I best remember him, he was sort of slightly built.
And not too outgoing or talkative.
I mean, they ran their program over there, YMCA, and they had other activities, you know.
It was a refuge.
I don't think I ever used it much as a refuge.
They had a barbershop there and a few other recreational activities.
Did you meet either of his sons?
Well, yes, I knew them very well, of course.
He served on a bank board with him.
No, but as students?
No, no, I didn't.
I guess Red must have been in school with me, but I think he's a little younger than I am.
And Jim?
Jim was even younger, I think.
No, no, Jim's the older one.
Oh, yeah, Jim was the football player.
Yes.
And Red was not, but he learned how to play.
That's right.
Jim was a good football player.
What about, was there Religious Emphasis Week then?
Oh, yes, they had Religious Emphasis Week.

and there was not too much separation of church and state in fact I guess that's one of the things that turned me off with the Lutheran program the minister at that time was a little too I guess I had a spirit of your religiosity is
something you do and don't get it from the outside.

This particular Lutheran minister took it on himself, because the churches were given the information from registration, who was Presbyterian, who was Lutheran, Catholic, and so forth, and they knew where you lived, and this Lutheran minister took it on himself to knock on doors at 8 o'clock in the morning in the dorm to remind them.
Lutheran students to come to church, and I guess I'd put Lutheran on them, and I resented that.

I mean, I thought that was a private morning, and you know, if I wanted to go to church, I would, but it kind of turned me off at the time, but I mean, there was a lot of, and they had the religious emphasis week, they had activities right here on the campus of outstanding ministers or speakers coming in and so forth.
Were there Sunday night?
Oh, Sunday night activities and Wednesday night, and you wouldn't,
Nothing else would be scheduled on Wednesday nights or on Sunday evenings.
Was there any food served?
Oh, yes, and girls were often there.
